      • setSelection

        public void setSelection(ClassCriteria.ClassType... classTypes)
        Sets the selected ClassCriteria.ClassTypes of the class hierarchy in the order they are selected. Default is ClassCriteria.ClassType.CLASSES, ClassCriteria.ClassType.INTERFACES.
        Parameters:
        classTypes - the ClassCriteria.ClassTypes of the class hierarchy that should be selected when iterating through the hierarchy. The classTypes should be unique. Otherwise, the first occurrence in the classTypes array wins. All later occurrences will be ignored.
        Since:
        1.2.0;

      • setSeparatedClassTypeTraversal

        public void setSeparatedClassTypeTraversal(boolean separatedClassTypeTraversal)
        If set to true the selected ClassCriteria.ClassTypes ( setSelection(ClassType...)) will be traversed in separation. Separation means that if the ClassCriteria.ClassTypes: ClassCriteria.ClassType.INTERFACES, ClassCriteria.ClassType.CLASSES is specified the interfaces will get traversed first using the set setTraverseStrategy(TraverseStrategy) and than the classes are traversed using the set ClassCriteria.TraverseStrategy. If separatedClassTypeTraversal is set to false the interfaces and classes tree will be traversed together in the set ClassCriteria.TraverseStrategy.
        Parameters:
        separatedClassTypeTraversal -
        Since:
        1.2.0;

      • setInterfacesIterationOrder

        public void setInterfacesIterationOrder(Comparator<Class<?>> interfacesComparator)
        A comparator that defines the order in which interfaces will be iterated. When Class.getInterfaces() is invoked the comparator that has been set is used to determine the order in which the interfaces are iterated. Default is a canonical class name comparator. Pass null to disable interface iteration order. In this case the interfaces will be iterated in the way the Class.getInterfaces() method returns them.
        Parameters:
        interfacesComparator -
        Since:
        1.0.0;

      • stopAt

        public void stopAt(Class<?> stopClass)
        The stopClass is the class or interface in the hierarchy where the iterator will stop iterating. If no stopClass is set (or null) the iterator will iterate through the hierarchy until no super class can be found (until Object - the Object class will be included). Otherwise the the iterator will stop at that class and not include it. 

         ClassCriteria criteria = new ClassCriteria();
 criteria.setTraverseOrder(TraverseOrder.SUPERCLASS_ONLY);

 criteria.stopAt(AbstractList.class);
 criteria.startAt(ArrayList.class);

 Iterator<Class<?>> classIterator = criteria.iterator();
 Class<?> currentClass = null;

 currentClass = classIterator.next();
 assertEquals(ArrayList.class, currentClass);

 currentClass = classIterator.next();
 assertEquals(AbstractList.class, currentClass);

 assertFalse(classIterator.hasNext());

        Parameters:
        stopClass -
        Since:
        1.0.0;

      • setTraverseClassesUniquely

        public void setTraverseClassesUniquely(boolean traverseClassesUniquely)
        If set to true the iterator traverses each class only one time. Interfaces as well as inner classes super types can occur multiple times in the class hierarchy. Therefore you might only want to iterate through a specific class one time instead of all occurrences. Default is false.
        Parameters:
        traverseClassesUniquely -
        Since:
        1.0.0;

      • add

        public void add(Predicate<Class<?>> predicate)
        Use the defined predicate as a filter when searching for elements. Multiple calls to this method will combine the predicates with a logical 'and' operator. The type of objects that the Predicate must be able to handle is defined by subclasses.

        The Predicate must handle Class objects in its Predicate.test(Object) method.

        Overrides:
        add in class ElementCriteria<Class<?>>
        Parameters:
        predicate - the predicate to use when filtering elements.
        Since:
        1.0.0;

      • getAnnotatedElementIterable

        public Iterable<? extends AnnotatedElement> getAnnotatedElementIterable(Class<?> startAt,
                                                                        Class<?> stopAt)
        Same behavior as getIterable(Class) but returns an Iterable whose iterator returns AnnotatedElements.
        Parameters:
        startAt -
        Returns:
        an Iterable that iterates through the class hierarchy as defined by this criteria starting at the given class. If the criteria defines a stop class than the Iterable will stop at that class.
        Throws:
        IllegalArgumentException - if the this criteria specifies a stop class and this class is not a superclass of the start class.
        Since:
        1.0.0;
